'''Jai Bhagwan Aggarwal''' ({{IPA-hns|d<U+0292>j b<U+02B1><U+0259>g<U+028B>an <U+0259>g<U+0259>r<U+028B>al|hi}}; born 4 April 1952) is an Indian politician from [[Delhi]]. He is a member of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP), the principal opposition party in the [[Indian Parliament]] and [[Legislative Assembly of Delhi]] (Delhi Vidhan Sabha). He is a Member of the Legislative Assembly of Delhi for Rohini Vidhan Sabha Constituency. He has never lost an election to the Vidhan Sabha.

==Early life==
Jai Bhagwan Aggarwal was born on 4 April 1952 in Naharpur village, Sector<U+2013>7, [[Rohini Sub City]], Delhi, to Shiv Narain Aggarwal. He obtained a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree from the [[University of Delhi]].<ref name="Profile">{{cite web | url=http://delhiassembly.nic.in/aspfile/whos_who/Jai_bhagwan.htm | title=List of Members <U+2013> Jai Bhagwan Aggarwal | publisher=Delhiassembly.nic.in. Legislative Assembly of Delhi | accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref>

==Political career==
Aggarwal is a member of the Bharatiya Janata Party,<ref name="Hindustan2013">{{cite news | title = Know Your MLA&nbsp;<U+2013> Jai Bhagwan Aggarwal, BJP | work = [[Hindustan Times]] | date = October 25, 2013 | accessdate = 16 November 2013 | url = http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-3108154721.html | location=[[New Delhi]] | publisher = via [[HighBeam Research]] }} {{Subscription required|via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref>  the main opposition party in the Indian Parliament and Delhi Vidhan Sabha.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/world/2013-09/13/c_125386810.htm | title=India's main opposition party names PM candidate for 2014 polls | date=13 September 2013 | agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]] | accessdate=19 November 2013 | publisher=News.xinhuanet.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-08-14/delhi/33200357_1_manish-sisodia-team-anna-political-alternative | title=Congress, BJP<U+2019>s poll rhetoric over Anna party | work=[[The Times of India]] | date=14 August 2012 | agency=Times News Network | accessdate=19 November 2013 | author=Pandit Ambika & Jha, Durgesh Nandan | location=[[New Delhi]]}}</ref>

He contested the Badli Vidhan Sabha Constituency in three consecutive elections from 1993 to 2003. At the 2008 state assembly election, he contested Rohini Constituency, carved out of Badli as a part of [[Boundary delimitation|delimitation]] of legislative assembly constituencies in 2008.<ref name="Hindustan2013" />

He was elected for the First Legislative Assembly of Delhi in 1993, defeating runner-up Rajesh Yadav of Indian National Congress (commonly known as the Congress) by a margin of 9,836 votes.<ref name="Hindustan2013" /> In the 1998 state assembly election, his margin of victory decreased more than half to 4,437 votes over runner-up Narain Singh Yadav of Congress.<ref name="Hindustan2013" /> He improved his margin of victory significantly in 2003 when he defeated Congress candidate Dharam Vir Yadav by 16,564 votes.<ref name="Hindustan2013" /> In the [[Delhi state assembly elections, 2008|2008 state assembly election]], he garnered 55,793 votes against 30,019 votes of Congress candidate Vijender Jindal, and won with 62.56 percent of the votes.<ref name="TOINov2013">{{cite news | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/assembly-elections-2013/delhi-assembly-elections/mostly-good-but-people-dont-credit-netas-for-it/articleshow/25615506.cms | title=Mostly good, but people don't credit netas for it | work=[[The Times of India]] | date=12 November 2013 | agency=Times News Network | accessdate=18 November 2013 | author=Akram, Maria | location=[[New Delhi]]}}</ref>

On 7 November 2013, the Bharatiya Janata Party announced Aggarwal as the party's candidate from Rohini Constituency for the [[Delhi state assembly elections, 2013|2013 state legislative assembly election]]; the election is scheduled to be held on 4 December.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/BJP-repeats-MLAs-to-play-safe-look-strong/articleshow/25337335.cms | title=BJP will field Vijendra Gupta against Sheila Dikshit | work=[[The Times of India]] | date=7 November 2013 | agency=Times News Network | accessdate=18 November 2013 | author=Alvi, Naziya | location=[[New Delhi]]}}</ref> He filed his nomination on 13 November 2013.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.asianage.com/delhi/89-file-poll-nominations-417 | title=89 file poll nominations | work=[[The Asian Age]] | date=14 November 2013 | agency=[[Press Trust of India]] | accessdate=18 November 2013 | location=[[New Delhi]]}}</ref> The former Delhi BJP president [[Vijender Gupta]] and office secretary S. K. Sharma wanted to contest from Rohini.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.jagran.com/delhi/new-delhi-city-10707087.html | title=<U+0915><U+093E><U+092C><U+093F><U+091C> <U+0938><U+0940><U+091F><U+094B><U+0902> <U+092A><U+0930> <U+092D><U+0940> <U+0926><U+093E><U+0935><U+0947><U+0926><U+093E><U+0930><U+094B><U+0902> <U+0915><U+0940> <U+0915><U+092E><U+0940> <U+0928><U+0939><U+0940><U+0902> | work=[[Dainik Jagran]] | date=7 September 2013 | accessdate=19 November 2013 | location=[[New Delhi]] | language=Hindi}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Jai Bhagwan is married to Krishna Aggarwal, and together they have three sons.<ref name="Profile" /> In 2006, the [[Delhi High Court]] ordered the [[Municipal Corporation of Delhi]] to demolish 18,000 properties, which were found to be illegally constructed. Aggarwal, who was living with his family at [[Saraswati Vihar]], [[Pitampura]], had his house demolished as "[t]he court order did not distinguish between the VIP's and the common people of Delhi". He claimed that his action would "change the image of the quintessential tainted Indian politician".<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-delhi-bjp-mla-demolishes-his-house-1007226 | title=Delhi BJP MLA demolishes his house | work=[[Daily News and Analysis]] | date=January 12, 2006 | accessdate=18 November 2013 | author=Singh, Sanghita | location=[[New Delhi]]}}</ref> He resides at New Swastik Apartment, Sector<U+2013>9, Rohini.<ref name="Profile" /> His interests include social and religious work and reading.<ref name="Profile" />

